x="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="563" y="271" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Person-affecting&lt;br&gt;view&lt;br&gt;[1+2+5+6+7+8+15+16+17]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   66k lives-eq/$1k · 70% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 30%&lt;br&gt;(Jan Narveson, Melinda Roberts)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + no_discounting_future_humans + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + space_expansion_backfires + living_in_simulation + person_affecting_view&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Person-affecting population ethics: making happy people is neutral, so the astronomical case for x-risk reduction — which rests on the sheer number of extra future lives saved from extinction — loses almost all its force. Only the harm to people who exist regardless still counts. This is the standard premise longtermism&#x27;s critics deny (discussed as the key objection in Greaves &amp; MacAskill&#x27;s &#x27;The Case for Strong Longtermism&#x27;). It requires no_discounting_future_humans, the astronomical-stakes move it pushes back on. || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 6 no_discounting_future_humans → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 15 space_expansion_backfires → 16 living_in_simulation → 17 person_affecting_view" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJzNWWtz2zYW%2FSt3PNuulFoyKVkve70zTiy3mXVSj%2BNsphNnFIiEJNQUwQVIy2qa%2FPYegA9RET1hVl%2F6xUOTwLnnPnEv9OnA5zOWBPEL6fODk4OjIzo7O6NbxURIsSRPsT%2FWeFiFdJd0HPeYVlIF%2FoPgK1q5k86kN%2BlPBpPhxO1N3P7EHVBDxzIid9A0QHchAM%2B1TpZRLGRI3gK4J%2BRQxJT0FoIFBtYddcilGVMTtmLrySJZslDnHzrEQrFkgZ5oueSrBYvzLz2aJXGieLZhsmRxzNVkJeLFxBfak0kYi3CeL%2B9TKMvvJ1u781WDQlwGxyaBLEQOSSezGVd2u%2FQSzf1CgR7piHl8wh8j4EHbyZR59zOheAHu9ikQD2azCCdaLJOAWbPknwcUcaWxk0GIZ0kaS1srjpm3ILYxpdDE6HodL%2FA8EwEnOGzzWR9RbEzFfF8fkuLwsghBRCoLp